I want to start off by saying that my heart goes out to the family and friends of the victims of the "Massacre at Virginia".

I was at home that&nbsp;afternoon and I happened to be watching the Young and the Restless and I saw the&nbsp;countdown clock that pops up when there is news about to interrupt&nbsp;the show.&nbsp; I thought to myself great, what happened now.&nbsp; The reported said "At least 20 people have been killed, please stay tuned as we will continue to keep you posted".&nbsp; I continue to watch the The Bold and the Beautiful and the countdown clock pops up again and this time she says, "at least 30 people have been killed", she tell me again to say tuned as she will continue to keep me posted.&nbsp;&nbsp;

The next day&nbsp; you turned on the television and you see that just about every morning show have decided to set camp on the campus of Virginia Tech.&nbsp; The competition begins, who can interview the most people, or who can interview the most important person.&nbsp; You are told time and time again that they are the most reliable source, that you heard it here first and so on and so forth.&nbsp; They all ask the same questions time and time again, what can we do to say our children, what was going to the mind of that student?&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;

When I first tuned in I was not moved.&nbsp; Everyday we ear that hundred of soldiers dieing &nbsp;over seas, not counting the number of innocent people that were killed that day as well.&nbsp; Over the period of the last 8 years, we have seen different school shootings, and the country mourns, for a week and two and we are on to the next big story.&nbsp; I was not moved at first because this has become a numbers game.&nbsp; As if they are saying the more people die the more tragic the event becomes.&nbsp; I started to feel a connection with the victims, when it is made known that these were actual humans.&nbsp; The&nbsp;numbers became names and stories of actual people.&nbsp; I started to think that what if one person was hurt, it would have not made such an impact and that is what is sad.&nbsp; It just seems to me that people have stop caring to the victims, but have begin to care about the story.&nbsp; There are about 11 people that survived and they are barely talked about, no they didn't die, but for the rest of their lives they have to think about that day.

Everyday there is a family sitting at home, hoping that today is not the day they there son or daughter or husband or&nbsp; wife or brother or sister, is not the one that was killed today.&nbsp; The families of the victims of any tragedy are always in remembrance of what occurred and I feel that at time the media at times is&nbsp;not sensitive of the mourners.

Its also sad when a tragedy is given a name, &nbsp;the Massacre&nbsp;at Virginia.&nbsp;&nbsp;

Another sad truth to this is that in a few weeks, it will no longer be in the news, while the Anna Nicole Smith death and battles are still being reported, months after her death.

Again my heart and my prayers are with all the victims of this tragic event.&nbsp; I pray that the Lord, our God keeps you all, in Jesus name, I pray,&nbsp; Amen.

Are you serious?&nbsp; A man was fired for the way that he called a women's basketball team "nappy-headed hos".&nbsp; Surprise, surprise of course he wasn't going to get away with it, he is after all in technical terms a white man .&nbsp;&nbsp; There is no may to really say how this would of been handled if he was a black man, but I think that he might of gotten suspended and have to make a public apology but being fired would of never happened.&nbsp; The things that people of color say about their own race and white people is a lot worse.&nbsp; This whole situation just goes to prove that race is a big issue in this country.&nbsp; Do you think that it would of been different if her just said hos instead?&nbsp; I think so, he probably would not have to apologize.&nbsp; 

I am not saying that Imus was justified for saying what he said, he was wrong, and so would anyone else, no matter what race.&nbsp; I believe that the man should of not been fired.&nbsp; I keep trying to put myself in the women's shoes, would I feel differently if he said that to me personally?&nbsp; Would I want him to lose his job?&nbsp; How long would I be upset?&nbsp; I know that I would be embarrassed because know I am know as a "nappy head ho".&nbsp; 

The true is that people say worst to friends and are never penalized for it, in fact it is followed by a laugh, yeah funny, ha ha ha.&nbsp; Why does it make it better when a woman calls another woman a B**** and depending on who calls you that, its fine.&nbsp; It means the same thing every time it is said, so why when said by someone outside the click its okay?&nbsp; 

Better yet the, N word, its okay for a black or hispanic person to use to call another black&nbsp; person but wrong when a white person uses it.&nbsp; It took for me to get to college to learn the reason behind that and it was not a good reason.&nbsp; I was told that when a black person says it, they are taking the negative aspect of the word and giving it a positive meaning, or something along those lines.&nbsp;&nbsp; What is that positive meaning?&nbsp; Anyone please feel free to answer that for me.... 

When Micheal Richards repeatedly said the N word, many people of color decided to make a movement to get other people of color to stop using that word.&nbsp; Their argument was how can you really get mad at anyone saying it when you say it yourself.&nbsp;&nbsp; Weeks later, they are back at using it again, now that this incident has risen up, people of color have become defensive again. 

By every definition of the American Race Placement system, I am considered to be black, not African American, but black.&nbsp; So when I fill in the job application, they let me know that it is my choice to fill that portion out if I want to, that it would not affect me in any way, I fill in Black/African American.&nbsp; The reason for that would be because I seem to get an interview when I do fill that portion out, as if I have met the quota, lol.&nbsp; This tells me that it doesn't really matter what I am but they know to expect a brown person to walk through the door.&nbsp; 

As I have written about before,&nbsp; this country is so race stricken.&nbsp; My point is that there are so many issues and race seems to have a role in this factor.&nbsp; With accomplishments and failures races to seem to always be a factor.
